---
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const envelopeLine = `{"ok":true,"status":"completed","work_complete":true,"children":[…64…]}`;
const statusLine = `[{"completed":64}]   # 202 s wall · 441 MB peak · single BEAM VM · zero extra OS processes per worker`;
const fallbackJson = `{"type":"provider_usage","data":{"active_transport":"http_sse",
  "transport_preference":"websocket","fallback_reason":"websocket_handshake_failed",
  "usage_available":true, …}}`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Pixir - Scale notes: 64 concurrent workers"
  description="Measured evidence for running up to 64 concurrent supervised subagent workers in one BEAM runtime versus one OS process per worker, on the same OpenAI quota. Memory, wall clock, transport pressure, kernel-tax marginals per worker, and honest caveats."
  canonical="https://pixir.dev/scale"
>
  <div class="page">
    <Header />

    <main id="top">
      <section class="section" id="scale">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">Evidence · Scale notes</p>
          <h2>One runtime vs. a herd of processes</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            The same question at three scales: what does it cost to run N coding-agent
            workers in parallel over one OpenAI quota? Pixir <code>delegate</code> — N
            supervised Subagent Sessions inside one BEAM runtime — against the common
            pattern today: one OS process per worker via <code>codex exec</code>.
            Measured, not projected, up to <strong>64 concurrent workers</strong>;
            synthetic load first, then real work. Pixir does not manufacture extra
            quota or capacity — it reduces process, token, and reconciliation overhead
            for the same account. The runtime speaks the OpenAI Responses dialect — the
            same wire contract the <a href="https://www.openresponses.org/specification">Open
            Responses</a> standard now formalizes. Today it binds to OpenAI's backends;
            conformance with open implementations is tracked direction, not a shipped
            feature.
          </p>

          <div class="terminal" role="group" aria-label="Terminal transcript of the 64-worker run">
            <div class="terminal-head">
              <span class="window-dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></span>
              <span>pixir · 64-worker fan-out · real run</span>
            </div>
            <div class="terminal-body">
              <div><span class="prompt">$</span> pixir delegate --spec docs/benchmarks/scale/audit64-spec.json --json --timeout-ms 480000</div>
              <div class="json">{envelopeLine}</div>
              <br />
              <div><span class="prompt">$</span> jq '[.children[].status] | group_by(.) | map(&#123;(.[0]): length&#125;)' envelope.json</div>
              <div class="ok">{statusLine}</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="proof-grid" role="group" aria-label="Headline results at 64 workers">
            <article class="proof">
              <code>441 MB vs 11,981 MB</code>
              <h3>27× memory at N=64</h3>
              <p>Peak RSS on real work: a single BEAM VM, adding zero OS processes per worker, against 91 processes: 1.4% versus 37% of a 32 GB machine.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="proof">
              <code>64/64 · both runtimes</code>
              <h3>Full completion, valid contracts</h3>
              <p>Every worker returned schema-valid strict JSON on both sides, with mutually consistent findings — cross-validation, not just throughput.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="proof">
              <code>31/673 calls</code>
              <h3>WebSocket pressure, zero losses</h3>
              <p>First systematic WS fallback appeared at 64 connections (4.6%). N=16 and N=32 ran clean; one N=8 ladder rep saw a single transient fallback. Every affected call degraded safely to SSE.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section alt">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">scale.memory</p>
          <h2>Marginal cost per worker is the story</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            Synthetic ladder N=1→8, three repetitions, bootstrap CI95 with zero overlap:
            <strong>6.5 MB</strong> (CI95 4.9–7.7) per additional child for <code>delegate</code>
            versus <strong>96.8 MB</strong> (CI95 95.9–97.5) per additional process, seeded and
            recomputable from the published evidence bundle. Everything
            solid below is measured; the projection exists only to size the wall and is
            drawn as one.
          </p>

          <div class="meter-panel" role="group" aria-label="Measured peak memory by scale">
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">N=32 · synthetic load</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:2.6%"></div></div><span class="mv">315 MB · 6 procs</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:35.6%"></div></div><span class="mv">4,265 MB · 309 procs</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">N=64 · real work — a 64-module documentation audit</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:3.7%"></div></div><span class="mv">441 MB · 1 VM</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">11,981 MB · 91 procs</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">Projection · N=150 on this 32 GB machine — not measured</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px proj" style="width:6%"></div></div><span class="mv">~1 GB proj.</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx proj" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">≳28 GB → swap proj.</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="meter-f">
              The projection scales the measured real-work footprint at N=64
              (11,981 MB across 64 processes ≈ 187 MB each; 441 MB for the shared
              VM) linearly to N=150: on 32 GB, the process-per-worker pattern is
              deep into swap around N≈150 while the shared runtime stays near a
              gigabyte. "Hundreds of agents" remains unmeasured —
              which is why the public claim is <strong>measured up to 64 concurrent
              workers</strong>, and nothing more.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">scale.kernel</p>
          <h2>What each extra worker costs the kernel</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            A second benchmark (proc-pressure) isolates the process-subsystem
            cost: same model and quota on both arms, synthetic ladder N=1→32,
            five repetitions, seeded bootstrap CI95 with zero overlap on every
            differentiating metric. Measured twice under labeled machine
            conditions: normal evening use, and a controlled low-ambient
            baseline (an engineered window, not a typical idle Mac; the
            procedure is disclosed in the bundle). The stamped low-ambient
            ladder is the primary table.
          </p>

          <div class="meter-panel" role="group" aria-label="Marginal kernel cost per additional worker">
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">threads (peak) per additional worker · point [CI95]</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:0.5%"></div></div><span class="mv">+0.0 [0.0, 0.0]</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">+100.5 [94.9, 104.4]</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">OS processes per additional worker</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:0.5%"></div></div><span class="mv">0 · flat at 6</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">+8.0 [7.1, 8.7]</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">involuntary context switches per additional worker</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:5.4%"></div></div><span class="mv">+2,445 [1.4k, 4.1k]</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">+45,018 [42.8k, 47.9k]</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">kernel CPU per additional worker</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:3.1%"></div></div><span class="mv">+0.04 s [0.03, 0.06]</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">+1.30 s [1.25, 1.37]</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="meter-f">
              A BEAM process is not an OS thread: pixir's tree stays flat at
              45 threads and 6 OS processes from N=1 to N=32, so the marginal
              is literally zero. Marginal RSS tells the memory section's story
              again: +3.7 MB versus +130.7 MB per worker. The context-switch
              ratio was similar under both machine conditions (18.5× loaded,
              18.4× quiet; point arithmetic, not a theorem) and the
              tree-scoped metrics moved within noise: the kernel tax tracks
              the process-per-worker architecture, not the busy machine.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="data-wrap">
            <table class="data">
              <thead>
                <tr><th scope="col">N=64 · real work</th><th scope="col">pixir · 64 workers</th><th scope="col">per-proc · 64 processes</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>threads / OS processes (peak)</td><td class="hl">45 / 6</td><td>6,111 / 474</td></tr>
                <tr><td>kernel CPU</td><td class="hl">16.9 s</td><td>187.1 s</td></tr>
                <tr><td>involuntary context switches</td><td class="hl">0.69 M</td><td>4.93 M</td></tr>
                <tr><td>wall</td><td>113 s</td><td>112 s (dead even)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>children completed</td><td>64/64</td><td>64/64</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p class="section-lead" style="margin-top: 18px;">
            The obvious counter: pixir children work deeper (~8.9 provider
            calls per child versus 1), so per-worker pressure could just be
            more work. The bundle normalizes per provider call from durable
            usage evidence: even per individual call, the process pattern pays
            <strong>34–55× the involuntary context switches</strong> and
            <strong>31–82× the kernel CPU</strong>, and its per-call tax grows
            with N while the shared runtime's stays flat. Creation cost points
            the same way (an in-VM worker spawns in ~1 µs versus ~42,500 µs
            for a process plus CLI boot), with the concession attached: at
            N≤64 the spawn tax amortizes to ~0.3 s total and is not the wall.
          </p>

          <div class="honesty-note" role="note">
            <p class="honesty-tag">honesty.rule</p>
            <p>
              The negative result leads: on the loaded-evening real-work
              ladder the process-per-worker baseline completed 205/205
              children; pixir completed 199/205. Six children died mid-run (3
              websocket reads, 1 websocket close, 2 provider server errors),
              each failing honestly with a resumable session id; three left
              partial output, preserved. That result motivated the runtime's
              bounded auto-retry, and the acceptance rerun completed 204/205
              with zero websocket-family deaths (directional, across two
              builds). Wall stayed nuanced: under low ambient the shared
              runtime won every N except a near-tie at N=1; under evening
              load, results were mixed. Raw speed is still not the claim.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="section-lead" style="margin-top: 18px;">
            Full method, machine conditions, corrections, and per-file map
            ship in the same evidence directory:
            <a href="https://github.com/Ranvier-Technologies/pixir/blob/main/docs/benchmarks/scale/proc-pressure-report.md">proc-pressure-report.md</a>
            and its 22 companion files.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section alt">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">scale.wall</p>
          <h2>The crossover appeared on synthetic load — and reversed on real work</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            Two workloads that must not be compared to each other: a synthetic ladder
            (trivial one-answer children) and the real audit (children reading whole
            modules in several passes). Read each group on its own.
          </p>

          <div class="meter-panel" role="group" aria-label="Wall clock by scale">
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">synthetic · N=16</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:14.3%"></div></div><span class="mv">28.9 s</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:10.6%"></div></div><span class="mv">21.4 s</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">synthetic · N=32 — crossover toward the shared runtime</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:12.4%"></div></div><span class="mv">25.0 s</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:18.9%"></div></div><span class="mv">38.2 s</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="meter-grp">
              <p class="meter-l">real work · N=64 — it reverses</p>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">pixir</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar px" style="width:100%"></div></div><span class="mv">202 s</span></div>
              <div class="mrow"><span class="mn">per-proc</span><div class="mtrack"><div class="mbar cx" style="width:47.5%"></div></div><span class="mv">~96 s †</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="meter-f">
              † max child; per-process timings are clean — the harness's total clock was
              contaminated by an orchestrator-side bug (ours, not the baseline's). Why
              the reversal? Pixir children worked deeper — 673 provider calls, ~10.5 per
              child, 65% more output than the baseline — and absorbed WebSocket pressure
              with retries. Raw speed was never the claim; the number is reported anyway.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="honesty-note" role="note">
            <p class="honesty-tag">honesty.rule</p>
            <p>
              The N=32 wall-clock crossover did not generalize to real work at N=64. Any
              public scale claim carries that nuance or is not made. Pixir's stable
              advantages are memory, process footprint, durable evidence, and
              backpressure — not raw per-run speed.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">scale.transport</p>
          <h2>WebSocket yields at 64; the design expected it</h2>

          <div class="data-wrap">
            <table class="data">
              <thead>
                <tr><th scope="col">ws concurrency</th><th scope="col">calls</th><th scope="col">fallbacks to sse</th><th scope="col">causes</th><th scope="col">children lost</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>N=8 · synthetic</td><td>16</td><td>1 (one rep)</td><td>unattributed · per-call reasons are not in the published ladder rows</td><td class="hl">0</td></tr>
                <tr><td>N=16</td><td>32</td><td>0</td><td>—</td><td class="hl">0</td></tr>
                <tr><td>N=32</td><td>68</td><td>0</td><td>—</td><td class="hl">0</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>N=64 · real</strong></td><td>673</td><td><strong>31 · 4.6%</strong></td><td>handshake_failed 17 · degraded 13 · closed 1</td><td class="hl">0</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <div class="terminal" role="group" aria-label="Provider usage log excerpt showing a safe transport fallback">
            <div class="terminal-head">
              <span class="window-dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></span>
              <span>provider_usage · append-only log · bounded excerpt</span>
            </div>
            <div class="terminal-body">
              <div class="dim"># real evidence of one safe fallback under 64-connection pressure</div>
              <div class="json">{fallbackJson}</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="section-lead" style="margin-top: 18px;">
            The <code>auto</code> transport policy — WebSocket preferred, SSE as a
            pre-output-safe fallback — earned its existence exactly where it should:
            under real pressure it degraded 31 calls and lost none. The transport
            evidence behind this, per-child transport counts and fallback-reason
            tallies, ships in
            <a href="https://github.com/Ranvier-Technologies/pixir/tree/main/docs/benchmarks/scale">the
            published scale-evidence bundle</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section alt">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">scale.evidence</p>
          <h2>The 64 runs produced real work, not benchmark theater</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            The N=64 workload was a documentation audit of this repository's 64 largest
            modules — the exact chore a freshly opened project needs. Each module was
            audited independently by both runtimes under the same strict JSON contract.
          </p>

          <div class="data-wrap">
            <table class="data">
              <thead>
                <tr><th scope="col">audit result</th><th scope="col">pixir · 64 workers</th><th scope="col">per-proc · 64 processes</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>schema-valid JSON contracts</td><td class="hl">64/64</td><td>64/64</td></tr>
                <tr><td>modules with major doc drift</td><td>7</td><td>8</td></tr>
                <tr><td>minor / clean</td><td>32 / 25</td><td>36 / 20</td></tr>
                <tr><td>consensus majors (both agree)</td><td colspan="2"><strong>4</strong> — independently double-evidenced findings</td></tr>
                <tr><td>uncached input tokens</td><td>1.47M</td><td>1.81M</td></tr>
                <tr><td>output produced</td><td>121k tok · ≈10.5 calls/child</td><td>73k tok · 1 turn/process</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p class="section-lead" style="margin-top: 18px;">
            Severity agreement between two mutually blind runtimes turns the four
            consensus findings into high-confidence, actionable results —
            parallelization as a <strong>verification method</strong>, not just
            throughput.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-inner">
          <p class="section-kicker">method.reproduction</p>
          <h2>Method, limits, and how to reproduce</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            Parity: same model and the same ChatGPT OAuth quota on both sides; isolated
            configuration homes on the same authorized account, excluding MCP servers
            and personal config from the comparison. RSS figures are sampled process-tree peaks (500 ms poll
            for the ladder, ~1 s for the N=64 samples), not
            OS-exact accounting. The synthetic ladder ran 3 repetitions; the 16/32/64
            scale points ran once each — directional, stated as such. Delegate fan-outs
            require <code>subagents.max_threads: N</code> in the spec or children queue
            at the default.
          </p>
          <p class="section-lead">
            Pixir is a developer preview. These are dogfood scale notes from one
            machine (macOS, 32 GB), published with their caveats attached. Primary
            evidence is machine-local by design — Pixir's evidence model keeps
            append-only session logs (with per-call <code>provider_usage</code> token
            and transport data) on the machine that ran them, so the numbers above
            are our runs, not a public dataset. Two redacted evidence bundles ship
            in-repo at <a href="https://github.com/Ranvier-Technologies/pixir/tree/main/docs/benchmarks/scale">docs/benchmarks/scale/</a>:
            the audit64 set (envelopes, per-child usage, ladder aggregates,
            CI95s, transport evidence, and the cross-validated audit findings)
            and the proc-pressure set (kernel-pressure ladders under two
            labeled machine conditions, per-call normalization, completion
            audits, failure evidence, and path-parameterized harness scripts,
            with its corrections log inside the report). The runtime ships
            everything needed to generate your own evidence:
            <a href="https://github.com/Ranvier-Technologies/pixir">try to break it and file what doesn't hold</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .meter-panel {
    margin-top: 26px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--canvas);
    padding: 20px 22px 8px;
  }
  .meter-grp { padding: 10px 0 8px; }
  .meter-grp + .meter-grp { border-top: 1px solid var(--line); }
  .meter-l {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .mrow {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 92px 1fr 168px;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 14px;
    padding: 3px 0;
  }
  @media (max-width: 560px) {
    .mrow { grid-template-columns: 68px 1fr 126px; gap: 8px; }
  }
  .mn { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--muted); }
  .mv {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
    text-align: right;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
  @media (max-width: 560px) {
    /* long values (CI intervals, "N MB · M procs") must wrap, not clip;
       this must come after the .mv rule so it wins the cascade */
    .mv { white-space: normal; }
  }
  .mtrack { height: 12px; display: flex; align-items: center; }
  .mbar { height: 12px; border-radius: 0 3px 3px 0; min-width: 3px; }
  .mbar.px { background: var(--beam-cyan); }
  .mbar.cx { background: var(--subtle); }
  .mbar.proj {
    opacity: 0.45;
    background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(
      45deg, transparent 0 5px, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.55) 5px 8px);
  }
  .meter-f {
    margin: 14px 0 10px;
    max-width: 640px;
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--subtle);
  }

  .honesty-note {
    margin-top: 24px;
    max-width: 720px;
    border: 1px solid #f3d9a4;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #fffbeb;
    padding: 16px 20px;
  }
  .honesty-tag {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: #b45309;
  }
  .honesty-note p:last-child {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .data-wrap {
    margin-top: 22px;
    overflow-x: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  table.data {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 14px;
    background: var(--canvas);
  }
  table.data th {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--subtle);
    text-align: left;
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  table.data td {
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
  }
  table.data tr:last-child td { border-bottom: 0; }
  /* sky-700: 5.93:1 on white (AA); sky-600 measured 4.09:1 and failed */
  table.data td.hl { color: #0369a1; font-weight: 620; }

  .terminal { margin-top: 26px; }
</style>
